Business Metrics Analysis¶

Research objective: analyse the results of the marketing campaign for the Procrastinate Pro+ app and find out why it is making losses

Data:

  • visits: visits_info_short.csv;
  • orders: orders_info_short.csv;
  • cost: costs_info_short.csv.

Course of research:

  1. Obtaining general information about the data
  2. Data preprocessing
    • column headers
    • data types
    • data gaps
    • duplicates
  3. Functions for calculating and analysing LTV, ROI, retention, and conversion
    • get_profiles()
    • get_retention()
    • get_conversion()
    • get_ltv()
    • filter_data()
    • plot_retention()
    • plot_converion()
    • plot_ltv_roi()
  4. Data analysis
    • users profiles
    • countries
    • devices
    • marketing channels
  5. Marketing
    • total amount spent on marketing
    • distribution of expenditures by advertising sources
    • visualisation of expenditure trends over time
    • customer acquisition cost
  6. Return on investment
    • LTV & ROI plots
    • user converions and its dynamics
    • user retention and its dynamcis
    • ROI by device
    • ROI by country
    • ROI by advertasing channel
    • user conversion by channel
    • user retention by channel
  7. Overall conclusion

Functions for calculating and analyzing LTV, ROI, retention, and conversion¶

Let's create functions for calculating and analyzing LTV, ROI, retention, and conversion.

These are functions for calculating metrics:

  • get_profiles() — for creating user profiles,
  • get_retention() — for calculating retention rate,
  • get_conversion() — for calculating conversion rate,
  • get_ltv() — for calculating customer lifetime value (LTV).

Functions for plots:

  • filter_data() — for smoothing data,
  • plot_retention() — for plotting retention rate,
  • plot_conversion() — for plotting conversion rate,
  • plot_ltv_roi — for visualizing customer lifetime value (LTV) and return on investment (ROI).

get_profiles()¶

In [20]:
def get_profiles(sessions, orders, ad_costs):

    profiles = (
        sessions.sort_values(by=['user_id', 'session_start'])
        .groupby('user_id')
        .agg(
            {
                'session_start': 'first',
                'channel': 'first',
                'device': 'first',
                'region': 'first',
            }
        )
        .rename(columns={'session_start': 'first_ts'})
        .reset_index()
    )

    profiles['dt'] = profiles['first_ts'].dt.date
    profiles['month'] = profiles['first_ts'].astype('datetime64[M]')

    profiles['payer'] = profiles['user_id'].isin(orders['user_id'].unique())

    new_users = (
        profiles.groupby(['dt', 'channel'])
        .agg({'user_id': 'nunique'})
        .rename(columns={'user_id': 'unique_users'})
        .reset_index()
    )

    ad_costs = ad_costs.merge(new_users, on=['dt', 'channel'], how='left')

    ad_costs['acquisition_cost'] = ad_costs['costs'] / ad_costs['unique_users']

    profiles = profiles.merge(
        ad_costs[['dt', 'channel', 'acquisition_cost']],
        on=['dt', 'channel'],
        how='left',
    )

    profiles['acquisition_cost'] = profiles['acquisition_cost'].fillna(0)

    return profiles

get_retention()¶

In [22]:
def get_retention(
    profiles,
    sessions,
    observation_date,
    horizon_days,
    dimensions=[],
    ignore_horizon=False,
):

    dimensions = ['payer'] + dimensions

    last_suitable_acquisition_date = observation_date
    if not ignore_horizon:
        last_suitable_acquisition_date = observation_date - timedelta(
            days=horizon_days - 1
        )
    result_raw = profiles.query('dt <= @last_suitable_acquisition_date')

    result_raw = result_raw.merge(
        sessions[['user_id', 'session_start']], on='user_id', how='left'
    )
    result_raw['lifetime'] = (
        result_raw['session_start'] - result_raw['first_ts']
    ).dt.days

    def group_by_dimensions(df, dims, horizon_days):
        result = df.pivot_table(
            index=dims, columns='lifetime', values='user_id', aggfunc='nunique'
        )
        cohort_sizes = (
            df.groupby(dims)
            .agg({'user_id': 'nunique'})
            .rename(columns={'user_id': 'cohort_size'})
        )
        result = cohort_sizes.merge(result, on=dims, how='left').fillna(0)
        result = result.div(result['cohort_size'], axis=0)
        result = result[['cohort_size'] + list(range(horizon_days))]
        result['cohort_size'] = cohort_sizes
        return result

    result_grouped = group_by_dimensions(result_raw, dimensions, horizon_days)

    result_in_time = group_by_dimensions(
        result_raw, dimensions + ['dt'], horizon_days
    )

    return result_raw, result_grouped, result_in_time

def get_conversion(
    profiles,
    purchases,
    observation_date,
    horizon_days,
    dimensions=[],
    ignore_horizon=False,
):

    last_suitable_acquisition_date = observation_date
    if not ignore_horizon:
        last_suitable_acquisition_date = observation_date - timedelta(
            days=horizon_days - 1
        )
    result_raw = profiles.query('dt <= @last_suitable_acquisition_date')

    first_purchases = (
        purchases.sort_values(by=['user_id', 'event_dt'])
        .groupby('user_id')
        .agg({'event_dt': 'first'})
        .reset_index()
    )

    result_raw = result_raw.merge(
        first_purchases[['user_id', 'event_dt']], on='user_id', how='left'
    )

    result_raw['lifetime'] = (
        result_raw['event_dt'] - result_raw['first_ts']
    ).dt.days

    if len(dimensions) == 0:
        result_raw['cohort'] = 'All users' 
        dimensions = dimensions + ['cohort']

    def group_by_dimensions(df, dims, horizon_days):
        result = df.pivot_table(
            index=dims, columns='lifetime', values='user_id', aggfunc='nunique'
        )
        result = result.fillna(0).cumsum(axis = 1)
        cohort_sizes = (
            df.groupby(dims)
            .agg({'user_id': 'nunique'})
            .rename(columns={'user_id': 'cohort_size'})
        )
        result = cohort_sizes.merge(result, on=dims, how='left').fillna(0)

        result = result.div(result['cohort_size'], axis=0)
        result = result[['cohort_size'] + list(range(horizon_days))]
        result['cohort_size'] = cohort_sizes
        return result

    result_grouped = group_by_dimensions(result_raw, dimensions, horizon_days)

    if 'cohort' in dimensions: 
        dimensions = []

    result_in_time = group_by_dimensions(
        result_raw, dimensions + ['dt'], horizon_days
    )

    return result_raw, result_grouped, result_in_time

get_ltv()¶

In [26]:
def get_ltv(
    profiles,
    purchases,
    observation_date,
    horizon_days,
    dimensions=[],
    ignore_horizon=False,
):

    last_suitable_acquisition_date = observation_date
    if not ignore_horizon:
        last_suitable_acquisition_date = observation_date - timedelta(
            days=horizon_days - 1
        )
    result_raw = profiles.query('dt <= @last_suitable_acquisition_date')
    result_raw = result_raw.merge(
        purchases[['user_id', 'event_dt', 'revenue']], on='user_id', how='left'
    )

    result_raw['lifetime'] = (
        result_raw['event_dt'] - result_raw['first_ts']
    ).dt.days

    if len(dimensions) == 0:
        result_raw['cohort'] = 'All users'
        dimensions = dimensions + ['cohort']

    def group_by_dimensions(df, dims, horizon_days):
        result = df.pivot_table(
            index=dims, columns='lifetime', values='revenue', aggfunc='sum'
        )
        result = result.fillna(0).cumsum(axis=1)
        cohort_sizes = (
            df.groupby(dims)
            .agg({'user_id': 'nunique'})
            .rename(columns={'user_id': 'cohort_size'})
        )
        result = cohort_sizes.merge(result, on=dims, how='left').fillna(0)
        result = result.div(result['cohort_size'], axis=0)
        result = result[['cohort_size'] + list(range(horizon_days))]
        result['cohort_size'] = cohort_sizes

        cac = df[['user_id', 'acquisition_cost'] + dims].drop_duplicates()

        cac = (
            cac.groupby(dims)
            .agg({'acquisition_cost': 'mean'})
            .rename(columns={'acquisition_cost': 'cac'})
        )

        roi = result.div(cac['cac'], axis=0)

        roi = roi[~roi['cohort_size'].isin([np.inf])]

        roi['cohort_size'] = cohort_sizes

        roi['cac'] = cac['cac']

        roi = roi[['cohort_size', 'cac'] + list(range(horizon_days))]

        return result, roi

    result_grouped, roi_grouped = group_by_dimensions(
        result_raw, dimensions, horizon_days
    )

    if 'cohort' in dimensions:
        dimensions = []

    result_in_time, roi_in_time = group_by_dimensions(
        result_raw, dimensions + ['dt'], horizon_days
    )

    return (
        result_raw,
        result_grouped,
        result_in_time,
        roi_grouped,
        roi_in_time
    )

filter_data()¶

In [28]:
def filter_data(df, window):
    for column in df.columns.values:
        df[column] = df[column].rolling(window).mean() 
    return df

plot_retention()¶

In [29]:
def plot_retention(retention, retention_history, horizon, window=7):

    plt.figure(figsize=(15, 10))

    retention = retention.drop(columns=['cohort_size', 0])
    retention_history = retention_history.drop(columns=['cohort_size'])[
        [horizon - 1]
    ]

    if retention.index.nlevels == 1:
        retention['cohort'] = 'All users'
        retention = retention.reset_index().set_index(['cohort', 'payer'])

    ax1 = plt.subplot(2, 2, 1)
    retention.query('payer == True').droplevel('payer').T.plot(
        grid=True, ax=ax1
    )
    plt.legend()
    plt.xlabel('Lifetime')
    plt.title('Retention of paying users')

    ax2 = plt.subplot(2, 2, 2, sharey=ax1)
    retention.query('payer == False').droplevel('payer').T.plot(
        grid=True, ax=ax2
    )
    plt.legend()
    plt.xlabel('Lifetime')
    plt.title('Retention of non-paying users')

    ax3 = plt.subplot(2, 2, 3)
    columns = [
        name
        for name in retention_history.index.names
        if name not in ['dt', 'payer']
    ]
    
    filtered_data = retention_history.query('payer == True').pivot_table(
        index='dt', columns=columns, values=horizon - 1, aggfunc='mean'
    )
    filter_data(filtered_data, window).plot(grid=True, ax=ax3)
    plt.xlabel('Acquisition date')
    plt.title(
        'The dynamics of retaining paying users on the {} day'.format(
            horizon
        )
    )

    ax4 = plt.subplot(2, 2, 4, sharey=ax3)
    filtered_data = retention_history.query('payer == False').pivot_table(
        index='dt', columns=columns, values=horizon - 1, aggfunc='mean'
    )
    filter_data(filtered_data, window).plot(grid=True, ax=ax4)
    plt.xlabel('Acquisition date')
    plt.title(
        'The dynamics of retaining non-paying users on the {} day'.format(
            horizon
        )
    )
    
    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

plot_conversion()¶

In [30]:
def plot_conversion(conversion, conversion_history, horizon, window=7):

    plt.figure(figsize=(15, 5))

    conversion = conversion.drop(columns=['cohort_size'])
    conversion_history = conversion_history.drop(columns=['cohort_size'])[
        [horizon - 1]
    ]

    ax1 = plt.subplot(1, 2, 1)
    conversion.T.plot(grid=True, ax=ax1)
    plt.legend()
    plt.xlabel('Lifetime')
    plt.title('Conversion')

    ax2 = plt.subplot(1, 2, 2, sharey=ax1)
    columns = [
        name for name in conversion_history.index.names if name not in ['dt']
    ]
    filtered_data = conversion_history.pivot_table(
        index='dt', columns=columns, values=horizon - 1, aggfunc='mean'
    )
    filter_data(filtered_data, window).plot(grid=True, ax=ax2)
    plt.xlabel('Acquisition date')
    plt.title('The conversion rate dynamics on the {} day.'.format(horizon))

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

def plot_ltv_roi(ltv, ltv_history, roi, roi_history, horizon, window=7):

    plt.figure(figsize=(20, 10))

    ltv = ltv.drop(columns=['cohort_size'])
    ltv_history = ltv_history.drop(columns=['cohort_size'])[[horizon - 1]]

    cac_history = roi_history[['cac']]

    roi = roi.drop(columns=['cohort_size', 'cac'])
    roi_history = roi_history.drop(columns=['cohort_size', 'cac'])[
        [horizon - 1]
    ]

    ax1 = plt.subplot(2, 3, 1)
    ltv.T.plot(grid=True, ax=ax1)
    plt.legend()
    plt.xlabel('Lifetime')
    plt.title('LTV')

    ax2 = plt.subplot(2, 3, 2, sharey=ax1)
    columns = [name for name in ltv_history.index.names if name not in ['dt']]
    filtered_data = ltv_history.pivot_table(
        index='dt', columns=columns, values=horizon - 1, aggfunc='mean'
    )
    filter_data(filtered_data, window).plot(grid=True, ax=ax2)
    plt.xlabel('Acquisition date')
    plt.title('LTV dynamics on the {} day'.format(horizon))

    ax3 = plt.subplot(2, 3, 3, sharey=ax1)
    columns = [name for name in cac_history.index.names if name not in ['dt']]
    filtered_data = cac_history.pivot_table(
        index='dt', columns=columns, values='cac', aggfunc='mean'
    )
    filter_data(filtered_data, window).plot(grid=True, ax=ax3)
    plt.xlabel('Acquisition date')
    plt.title('Users acquisition cost dynamics')

    ax4 = plt.subplot(2, 3, 4)
    roi.T.plot(grid=True, ax=ax4)
    plt.axhline(y=1, color='red', linestyle='--', label='Retunr on investment')
    plt.legend()
    plt.xlabel('Lifetime')
    plt.title('ROI')

    ax5 = plt.subplot(2, 3, 5, sharey=ax4)
    columns = [name for name in roi_history.index.names if name not in ['dt']]
    filtered_data = roi_history.pivot_table(
        index='dt', columns=columns, values=horizon - 1, aggfunc='mean'
    )
    filter_data(filtered_data, window).plot(grid=True, ax=ax5)
    plt.axhline(y=1, color='red', linestyle='--', label='Retunr on investment')
    plt.xlabel('Acquisition date')
    plt.title('ROI dynamics on {} day'.format(horizon))

    plt.tight_layout()
    plt.show()

Overall conclusion¶

We analysed the advertising campaign results for the Procrastinate Pro+ app.

We were provided with data from 1 May to 27 October 2019 - 6 months.

Ads were bought on 10 channels:

  • TipTop,
  • RocketSuperAds,
  • YRabbit,
  • FaceBoom,
  • MediaTornado,
  • AdNonSense,
  • LeapBob,
  • WahooNetBanner,
  • OppleCreativeMedia,
  • lambdaMediaAds

and was active in four countries:

  • US,
  • United Kingdom,
  • France,
  • Germany

We found out the percentage of paying users for each country:

  • USA - 6.9%
  • Germany - 4.11%
  • Great Britain - 3.98%
  • France - 3.8%

The most promising country for the app is the USA, as this country has the most users and simultaneously the highest percentage of paying users. Users attracted in this country are most likely to move to paying status.

The app is used on 4 types of devices:

  • MS
  • MAC
  • Andriod
  • iPhone

the most paying users on MAC and iPhone devices - 6.36% and 6.21 respectively. The least is on personal computers.

105'497 was spent on advertising during the period under review. Most of the total amount was invested in the channels

  • TipTop - 51.90%
  • FaceBoom - 30.75%

The other 8 channels accounted for only 17% of the total budget.

We excluded organic users from the analysis. The app has a lot of organic users (56439 thousand), but they convert very poorly into paying users. It has the smallest percentage of converting users to paying status - 2.06%. The app clearly needs advertising, so we decided to focus on analysing the results of the advertising campaign on different channels.

At the stage of analysing the dynamics of spending changes over time, we found out that spending on the TipTop channel was steadily growing. The same trend was reflected in the dynamics of the cost of attracting one client: CAC on this channel rose every month, while this indicator remained at the same level on the other channels.

FaceBoom channel is the second most expensive advertising channel. The cost here doesn't spike like the TipTop channel, but remains the most expensive when compared to the other 8 channels.

When we checked the ROI of the advertising campaign as a whole, we found out that it did not pay off.

The reason is the inefficiency of advertising in the US. The advertising campaigns in the rest of the countries paid off during the first half of the period under review, but the advertising campaign in the US was so ineffective that it dragged the overall result to a loss.

Next, we looked at the results of advertising in the US on different channels and found that there are 5 channels operating in the US:

  • FaceBoom
  • MediaTornado
  • RocketSuperAds
  • TipTop
  • YRabbit

of which 3 paid off at the beginning of the period under review, and 2 never turned a profit: FaceBoom and TipTop

The reason for the unprofitable advertising campaign as a whole is that 83% of the total budget was allocated to unprofitable channels.

Advertising in other countries (except for the US) pays off very well, hence there is no need to adjust advertising campaigns in these countries.

There needs to be a change of strategy in the US.

This is the most promising country for the app. It is necessary to redirect advertising investments to more efficient channels.

The TipTop channel is too expensive, the cost of attracting one user on it is constantly growing. It is necessary to stop working with this channel.

FaceBoom channel. The situation with this channel is ambiguous. On the one hand, there is a very good percentage of attracting users and converting them into paying users; on the other hand, this channel does not pay off for two reasons: too expensive advertising, very poor retention rate. We recommend to check:

  • Is there a possibility to reduce the cost of advertising on this channel? Perhaps choose another plan.
  • Check what is the reason for the low retention rate of users coming from this channel. There might be some technical problem.

If it is possible to fix these two problems, you can continue working with this channel. If there is no such possibility, it is better to stop working with this channel.

We recommend switching to the following channels, prioritising them in this order:

  1. the most promising channel - RocketSuperAds. The percentage of users switching to paying status here is 7.91% and the user retention rate is quite high.

  2. YRabbit. The percentage of paying users - 3.83%, good retention rate, low cost of user acquisition - 0.25, which leads to a very good ROI. This channel paid off better than all the others, by ~260%.

  3. MediaTornado. This channel has the same low cost per user - 0.25, and it paid off almost as well as the YRabbit channel. But it has the smallest (of these 3 channels) percentage of paying users - 3.57%, and also user retention is worse here than on the other 2 channels. That's why we put it on the third place.

Very little money was invested in these channels:

  • 1,74%
  • 0,9%
  • 0,9% of the total budget, respectively.

Advertising on each of these three channels paid off by more than 200%.
